I feel like this has a lot of features that look great on paper. But to me, it seems like a lot of money for a plug and play system in a capacity where you really dont want something plug and play. Someone buying this and taking it out overlanding through wilderness thinking the price makes it infallible or drastically underestimating the amount of skill and knowledge is needed for certain trails etc is in for a really rough awakening when they realize one of those prefabricated systems crapped out or they have no idea how to use it.   I dont mind overbuilt things, I tend to overbuild myself. But I feel like if youre going to be taking a rig through areas where your only way out is through, you should know every single inch of that machine, how it works, where everything is in relation to other items, and how to pull it out, bang on it and administer a field repair if necessary. This strikes me as a land titanic: so many overbuilt systems the possibility of something going horribly wrong is theoretically reduced but if and when it does it will be all the more terrible. Not to mention for the better part of a million bucks taking that thing anywhere off pavement seems like a worse financial move than buying an expensive renaissance painting and using it as a dart board. This thing strikes me as the sort of thing some millionaire influencer might park at Coachella to make people think theyre more into the outdoors than they actually are, or something someone who wants the tiny house or van life on paved or level roads but is terrified of having something go wrong might get if they dont mind spending what it would cost for an actual house in many areas. Its neat, but idk if its worth that much. Id love to be proven wrong though.

Id have to disagree however many years ago might have made a similar statement.   First, we have the rig being an F550. Most of these are destined to work and come appropriately stripped with a 80k price. To have one built with all the interior options of the more common F350 plus exterior bling like mounding and doorbhandles that aren't from the Amish Package, and I'll guess the cab and chassis came in at close to 125 or 130.  Next... Carbon Fiber. Not much needs to be said on that front but this beast is made FROM it. Not accented, not highlighted with or essences of it. It's MADE of it. Imma guess 100k in carbon fiber just for the shell.  Next up we have the biggest toteboard of 'Let's Get Small'. Price per square inch on a motor home gets exponentially larger the smaller one goes. Eventually there is a balance point but it's a rule that makes sense after one gets over the initial shock. Going Small yet keeping the expected functionality costs more with tighter spaces for behind the scenes plumbing / wiring etc as well as for the fixed cost of the thing itself. Poor example but what comes immediately to mind is extend-Range or performance of an electric vehicle requires either more batteries or better performing batteries that fit in the same space available for the standard ones yet offer more capacity. Going smaller yet expecting same or bigger will cost ya no matter how its sliced. Toss in another 100k or this and the other etc's plus labor which is not piece work but craftsmanship level crew.   Then throw in all the touches like plate and silverware slots that keep the rig quiet while driving (huge, trust me on that or try listening to glasses clink and crap rattles for 300 miles on the way to the camp. )  Every where one looks, this rig is filled with this type of unexpected design and thought that oh just so happens to be wrapped in higher-end finishes and or materials. Check another 100k here.  Lastly, wheels, leveling, power plant. God knows how many stage paint, bumper boxes etc and it's bespoke without actually being bespoke. But I bet they welcome call outs. Either way...pop another 100k to the bill for this and installs and integration with everything else. Oh and make sure it all can survive extreme swings in Temps, being shaken and bumped as well being potentially invaded by mud, critters and moisture that is magically repelled for years.  So far, I'm up to 425k but very likely have missed a good number of items so I'll use a standard overrun factor of 30% to account for it bringing my final estimate to basically 600k.  Dealer ask is around 700k. They ain't getting rich at that point which is why earlier I remarked in another comment of expecting 900k. Or more.  This is a bargain.

Respectfully, most of y'all are so wrong its almost painful to read. Here's why:  First, we have the rig being an F550. Most of these are destined to work and come appropriately stripped with a 80k price. To have one built with all the interior options of the more common F350 plus exterior bling like mouldings and doorbhandles that aren't from the Amish Package, and I'll guess the cab and chassis came in at close to 125 or 130.  Next... Carbon Fiber. Not much needs to be said on that front but this beast is made FROM it. Not accented, not highlighted with or essences of it. It's MADE of it. Imma guess 100k in carbon fiber just for the shell.  Next up we have the biggest toteboard of 'Let's Get Small'. Price per square inch on a motor home gets exponentially larger the smaller one goes. Eventually there is a balance point but it's a rule that makes sense after one gets over the initial shock. Going Small yet keeping the expected functionality costs more with tighter spaces for behind the scenes plumbing / wiring etc as well as for the fixed cost of the thing itself. Poor example but what comes immediately to mind is extend-Range or performance of an electric vehicle requires either more batteries or better performing batteries that fit in the same space available for the standard ones yet offer more capacity. Going smaller yet expecting same or bigger will cost ya no matter how its sliced. Toss in another 100k or this and the other etc's plus labor which is not piece work but craftsmanship level crew.   Then throw in all the touches like plate and silverware slots that keep the rig quiet while driving (huge, trust me on that or try listening to glasses clink and crap rattles for 300 miles on the way to the camp. )  Every where one looks, this rig is filled with this type of unexpected design and thought that oh just so happens to be wrapped in higher-end finishes and or materials. Check another 100k here.  Lastly, wheels, leveling, power plant. God knows how many stage paint, bumper boxes etc and it's bespoke without actually being bespoke. But I bet they welcome call outs. Either way...pop another 100k to the bill for this and installs and integration with everything else. Oh and make sure it all can survive extreme swings in Temps, being shaken and bumped as well being potentially invaded by mud, critters and moisture that is magically repelled for years.  So far, I'm up to 425k but very likely have missed a good number of items so I'll use a standard overrun factor of 30% to account for it bringing my final estimate to basically 600k.  Dealer ask is around 700k. They ain't getting rich at that point which is why earlier I remarked in another comment of expecting 900k. Or more.  This is a bargain.

Or I can just say it without being kind: The actual people who can afford to purchase this and will do just that, can see the value here and that has nothing to do with being stupid or gullible.   All these 'I can get me a  ford for 35k and put a box on it, for 5k so that means they outrageously overpriced' posters will have little to no impact and will be read only out of amusement or great concern about our public schools prior to reading one that is actually relevant and intelligent.
